Refactoring the rocket animation in Racket

2,470 views2.4K views
101Share
Share
10 / 1
Nic McPhee
Published on 29 Aug 2012
Subscribe 225
A longer demonstration of using refactoring to remove duplication and clean up some simple animation code in Racket. This is based directly on the extended example in Section 1.4 of Chapter 1 of the 2nd edition of How to Design Programs. This was created for the CSci 1301 (Problem Solving and Algorithm Development) at the University of Minnesota, Morris. One thing I forgot to emphasize in the video: Try reading the refactored code out loud and compare that experience to reading the original version out loud. Things like "if the height is less than or equal to the height of the middle of the rocket when it's landed..." are a lot more readable than "if the height is less than or equal to [some non-trivial math that doesn't read well]" that we started with. My home page: http://www.morris.umn.edu/~mcphee UMM Computer Science: http://www.morris.umn.edu/academics/c... UMM: http://www.morris.umn.edu 2nd Edition of How to Design Programs: http://www.ccs.neu.edu/home/matthias/... Racket: http://racket-lang.org/ DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) Principle at Wikipedia: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don't_re... Refactoring at Wikipedia: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_ref...

Nic McPhee Nic McPhee 5 years ago
You essentially want "clock arithmetic" for something like that (where a clock goes from 11 to 12 and back to 1). This is typically called "modular arithmetic" in both mathematics and programming. In Racket the function (remainder x y) is likely to be useful; it returns the remainder of dividing x by y. Play around with that some and see if it gets you where you want to go.
